A: The quality of the image is degraded because you are not compressing the image after resizing it. When you resize an image, you are just changing its size, not its quality. If you want to keep the quality of the image, you should compress it after resizing.
Here is a simple example of how you can compress an image after resizing it:
```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    try {
        BufferedImage originalImage = ImageIO.read(new File("path_to_your_image"));
        BufferedImage resizedImage = resizeImage(originalImage, 200, 200);
        File outputFile = new File("path_to_save_resized_image");
        ImageIO.write(resizedImage, "jpg", outputFile);
    } catch (IOException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    }
}

private static BufferedImage resizeImage(BufferedImage originalImage, int targetWidth, int targetHeight) throws IOException {
    BufferedImage resizedImage = new BufferedImage(targetWidth, targetHeight, BufferedImage.TYPE_INT_RGB);
    Graphics2D graphics2D = resizedImage.createGraphics();
    graphics2D.drawImage(originalImage, 0, 0, targetWidth, targetHeight, null);
    graphics2D.dispose();
    return resizedImage;
}
```
In this example, the `resizeImage` method resizes the image
